metadata.name: Dreamcatcher Forest #143
metadata.description:
"Dreamcatcher Forest" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Art Basel, Basel 2022. The illustration in this work draws inspiration from Native American dreamcatchers, a protective talisman crafted from beautifully intricate patterns of woven thread, built from natural materials & colorful beads.

Dreamcatchers are used to protect dreamers while they sleep. Good dreams are able to slip through the web to meet the sleeper beneath, while bad dreams are trapped and prevented.

- Use the "S" key to save a PNG image.
- Use the "P" key to export a print-quality image.

metadata.name: Layers #15
metadata.description:
It's the first time I really delved into studying about P5JS

I spent the last one collecting generative art and it made my passion for all this just grow, as a collector I wanted to move forward and want to do something more and so developed this project. 

I've been a designer for almost 10 years, an art director for over 1 year, I work all day with design every day, Photoshop and its infinite layers haunt me all day, as my passion wanted to insert something related there in my work so I thought of "layers" and thus "Layers" was born, layers and layers, specifically of rectangles one on top of the other forming the interactions of this work.

5 Styles:

Dunes:
Curves, some sharp and others less so, some remind me of sand dunes.

moiree:
It reminds me a little of compositions with a MoirÃ© effect, forming curves where there is the presence of shadows giving relief.

Arranged:

A style where there is a certain organization of lines, but not perfect.

Strips:

Strips of colors on top of each other.

Harmonic:
It forms flat compositions, they are more organized layers.

metadata.name: Lianas #14
metadata.description:
This piece is inspired by op'art and physics simulation. A perfect structure is created at first and gets destructed by repulsing forces making the whole edifice deform itself.

Thechnically this work is a grid of nodes that repel each other. Each node on each row is connected to its neighboor with a digital spring maintaining the equilibrium.

A random number of repulsing nodes are placed randomely on each generation, making the lines move from their initial alignment.

Final image is generated in about 500 frames as nodes stop to move.

metadata.name: z-pattern : stacked noise #2
metadata.description:
This work is an exploration of pattern interferences that can happen in depth perception.

Each token is composed of 35 frames stacked in the z-axis. Each frame is a simple noise field with several detail levels displayed on transparent background.

The 3D stack is oriented at random for each token.

This work is interactive : you can press and drag your mouse around the canvas to explore different views and see several patterns.
